{
  "text": "To delineate the brain parenchymal damage, lesion volume was measured on DWI-MRI. Hyperintensity on DWI correlated well with infarct volume on histologic sections (r = 0.76, P = 0.001), which was similar to the results of an earlier study [CITATION_1] ). An abnormally hyperintense signal on DWI was detected already 2.5 hours after MCAO and became more extensive 24 hours after MCAO. In TT-tMCAO, NBO and HBO significantly reduced lesion volume on DWI compared with air ( Figure 1) . In contrast, in CT-tMCAO, only a transient trend toward reduced lesion volume was detected on DWI-MRI in the HBO group at 2.5 hours but no differences were seen at 24 hours after tMCAO (Figure 1 ). Hence, oxygen therapy did not reduce lesion volume in permanent tMCAO. ",
